            "team_handle": "torproject", 
            "message": "Hello Rbcafe,\n\nI don't understand exactly what you mean here. The `X-Your-Address-Is` HTTP header displays the IP address of the client visiting that webserver: I tested that, and when I visit without Tor it shows my actual IP, whereas when I visit with Tor it shows the exit node's IP address. That's what it's supposed to be doing. Why are you implying that this leaks IP addresses? And what does this have to do with crashing?\n\nThanks!", 
            "markdown_message": "<p>Hello Rbcafe,</p>\n\n<p>I don&#39;t understand exactly what you mean here. The <code>X-Your-Address-Is</code> HTTP header displays the IP address of the client visiting that webserver: I tested that, and when I visit without Tor it shows my actual IP, whereas when I visit with Tor it shows the exit node&#39;s IP address. That&#39;s what it&#39;s supposed to be doing. Why are you implying that this leaks IP addresses? And what does this have to do with crashing?</p>\n\n<p>Thanks!</p>\n", 
            "type": "Activities::BugNeedsMoreInfo", 
            "id": 3348382, 
            "genius_execution_id": null
        }, 
        {
            "automated_response": false, 
            "created_at": "2018-09-17T11:29:34.408Z", 
            "is_internal": false, 
            "editable": false, 
            "updated_at": "2018-09-17T11:29:34.408Z", 
            "actor": {
                "username": "rbcafe", 
                "url": "/rbcafe", 
                "profile_picture_urls": {
                    "medium": "https://profile-photos.hackerone-user-content.com/000/088/977/566d014a5c7d11fcbe5871348a2dec54a7474a89_medium.jpg?1476407531"
                }, 
                "hackerone_triager": false
            }, 
            "team_handle": "torproject", 
            "message": "Greetings,\n\nThe question I ask to myself is : \"why there is a X-Your-Address-Is header inside a response for a regular call without a TOR Browser\" . \n\nIf this header gives information about the node, shouldn't it be reserved only in a specific case : TorBrowser calling Tor Relay. \n\nI'm implying that it leaks IP because the data can be fetched by users without TOR and can be cached. (as in example).\n\nIn a particular crash and user switching from proxy to non-proxy the IP of the user would be revelled.\n\nEven if \" it's supposed to be doing\" don't you feel that this data could be stripped out when a non TOR Browser connects to a TOR Relay ?\n\nBest regards\n\nRbcafe\n", 
            "markdown_message": "<p>Greetings,</p>\n\n<p>The question I ask to myself is : &quot;why there is a X-Your-Address-Is header inside a response for a regular call without a TOR Browser&quot; . </p>\n\n<p>If this header gives information about the node, shouldn&#39;t it be reserved only in a specific case : TorBrowser calling Tor Relay. </p>\n\n<p>I&#39;m implying that it leaks IP because the data can be fetched by users without TOR and can be cached. (as in example).</p>\n\n<p>In a particular crash and user switching from proxy to non-proxy the IP of the user would be revelled.</p>\n\n<p>Even if &quot; it&#39;s supposed to be doing&quot; don&#39;t you feel that this data could be stripped out when a non TOR Browser connects to a TOR Relay ?</p>\n\n<p>Best regards</p>\n\n<p>Rbcafe</p>\n", 
            "type": "Activities::BugNew", 
            "id": 3348417, 
            "genius_execution_id": null
        }, 
